Introduction
•A password manager is a computer program that allows users to store, generate, and manage
their passwords for local applications and online services.
•A password manager assists in generating and retrieving complex passwords, storing such
passwords in an encrypted database, or calculating them on demand. Depending on the type
of password manager used on the functionality offered by its developers, the encrypted
database is either stored locally on the user's device or stored remotely through an online file
hosting service. Password managers typically require a user to generate and remember one
"master" password to unlock and access any information stored in their databases. Many
password manager applications offer additional capabilities that enhance both convenience
and security such as storage of credit card and frequent flyer information and autofill
functionality.
•Password managers enable the use of strong and unique passwords for each online
account and provide an efficient way to manage all the passwords. The login
information is encrypted and stored in either the local memory of the user’s system or
in cloud storage. Portable password manager applications installed in mobile devices
can also be used as a way to manage and remember passwords anywhere and use
them on shared systems.
•Password managers usually incorporate some additional features like automatic form
filling and password generation. The automatic form filling feature fills in the login
information for a particular URL whenever it loads, and thus reduces manual errors
and protects systems from hacker attacks such as keylogging. unique and random
passwords for each account
•Passwords have been used with computers since the earliest days of computing.
•In 1961, Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) creates the computer password so
that multiple people can use a shared computer system. Each user needed an individual
password to access the system, and usage time was tracked. All of the passwords were
stored in the system.
•In 1962, Researcher Allan Scheer used the time share computer system at MIT for his
research, but he could only use the system for four hours a week. So he found a way to
print out the password list, and he was able to “hack” in as other users to get around the
time limit. So the very next year after the computer password was invented, hacking had
already started!
History
•In 1970s Cryptographer Robert Morris develops “hashing”: this system translates a
password into a numerical value, and the password isn’t stored physically on the
computer.
•However, despite all the time that has gone by and all the advances in computer
systems, password-based systems to this day remain a security standard. And they
remain vulnerable.
•This is largely because the passwords people use are overly simple (users tend to
make them short and easy to remember) and because many systems allow a user to
guess multiple times and/or enable password hints or even “forgot my password” reset
options.
Proposed Project Details
•Password managers have become a necessity in modern society due to the
increasingly large number of unique passwords that people are forced to
maintain, We know the fact that many websites do not take week passwords
there passwords are very hard to remember.
•Most of the password managers use reversible encryption to store all types of
passwords. For these reasons, we cannot trust these password manager for the
security purpose. Our team provide a design of password manager that is
providing synchronization without the need for encryption .
•It also does not require the trust of the password manager. In our project of
password manager the user can store there ID’s and password in the system.
•After viewing the password the user can log in into his/her corresponding website.
The plus point of our project is that it is user friendly and it does not require any
type of internet connections from from the user. User can access the password
manager from Microsoft windows.
•The major weakness of the system is its user friendliness. By performing this
project we are able to discover the feasibility of several security techniques for
example encryption. We are able to do this project under the guidance of our DT
professor Abhishek sir . This project is completely done by using python as
programming language .
Comparison
•Due to the ever-growing number of hacking attempts and the constant data leaks
involving major companies like Google, internet users are paying more and more
attention to keeping account credentials as safe as possible by implementing strong
passwords.
•However, memorizing tens if not hundreds of different logins for each account is
humanly impossible, especially if they are as complex as then need to be for proper
security. Password managers help recall any login details –among other things –
but since their most important features are basically all the same, picking the right
software can be tough even for the most informed users.
•With side by side comparison here are the top password manager of 2022:
1. Dashlane –BE FOR EXTRA SECURITY FEATURES
2. LogMeOnce. –BEST MULTI-DEVICE PLATFORM
3. Bitwarden –BEST FREE OPTION
4. RememBear –BEST FOR NEW USERS
5. 1Password –BEST FOR FAMILIES
6. LastPass –OVERALL BEST
Conclusion
•The first contribution of this study is a successful case of implementing
password managers in a multiple-password environment that can be
replicated on other organizations. It is shown that factors like using weak
passwords, reusing passwords, using password notes, and so forth are very
much improved when introducing password managers into the organization.
•The second contribution is a confirmation of previous studies regarding
password management in multiple-password environments. When comparing
it to previous studies it's very clear that strict policies and multiple-passwords
creates many security issues in organizations even today. The password
manager is just one way of many that can help improve the password
management in organizations.
